            <span id="ChapterParagraphTwo">
            I remember when he was gambling in Hong Kong—converting our garage into a gambling casino, because that was the only way he knew how to make money—he would keep us busy by telling us, "Why don't you draw something on the floor? Those spirits that you draw will come up at night and dance." We loved that. We would be drawing beautiful people on the floor of the garage so that they would get up at night and dance with us. Since we were kids running around with nothing to do, that was one way he kept us busy. I'm sure he didn’t believe that was true, but he somehow made us believe it was.   
            </span>
            <span id="SEE_MORE"><a href="#" id="restofstory-show"  onclick="showHide('restofstory');return false;">SEE MORE</a>
            </span>

            <div id="restofstory" class="more">
                <span id="ChapterParagraphTwo">
                    He was a very kind person. He would allow strangers to come into the house and stay with us without asking questions. He housed several people. One boy was about thirteen years old, and his mom walked in front of our garage one day and said, "I have no food. I have no money. Can you take care of my son?” My dad was probably thinking in his own mind, "We don't have enough food for our own family. How can we accept you?" But he was so generous. He took him in and housed that boy for four or five years. Wherever we moved, the boy would move with us, and he would help with little chores left and right. He finally went to work in the police academy. It was not only one boy; there was another boy, too. He also came, and my dad accepted him. He was thirteen or fourteen years old. They were good kids. They had family problems, but my parents accepted them to come and stay with us.
                    <br /><br />

                    Back to my dad's spirituality. He believed in good things. If you do good things, good things will come to you. After he moved to America, he wasn't a church-goer, and he didn't have time to discuss the gospel or even sit down and listen to the Gospel. It’s understandable, with the little bit of money he had in his pocket, and he had to feed us. Many nights, we were still hungry while we were sleeping. He didn't have enough food for all of us to eat. I still remember we mixed two eggs with a lot of water so all of us would have something to eat. That went on in Hong Kong, and it still went on when we were in Hawaii. 
                    <br /><br />

                    When he was in his fifties, he started wondering more about God, and then he read a lot of books and fell in love with Buddhism. He believed that if you do bad, something bad will happen to you. In his life, he had so many bad people do bad things to him. I would scream and yell, and I said, "Dad, how can you let people do this to you?" He was such a kind person. He made good 叉燒包, and he would go out to the streets of Hawaii to sell it. People became jealous, took away his license, and said, “You cannot sell 叉燒包 anymore." And then they set up all of these rules. “You cannot do this; you cannot do that.” He struggled to feed the family. Later, there was a stranger about his age who asked him, “What are you doing? I would like to learn from you." He would be so generous in teaching this man how to do business. He learned from my dad, then took over everything and squeezed my dad out of the business. I didn't like that, but my dad was very kind. He would accept it and say, "Okay. That's life. Don't worry." 
                    <br /><br />

                    Once, his eye suddenly went blind; he had a retinal detachment. He went to see the doctor right away, but the doctor probably didn't have enough knowledge, and then didn't refer him to a specialist. He lost his eyesight. After I went to medical school, I learned that if you have a retinal detachment, you have to fix it within 24 hours. That doctor did not fix my dad's eye within 24 hours. He fixed it about three or four days later, and so my dad was blind in one of his eyes ever since. He could have sued that doctor, but he decided not to. He said, "Evelyn, everybody has problems in life. I don't need to add more problems to this doctor. The curse will come back to you for that." He never sued him. His kindness was extraordinary. He was kind to everybody, so everybody took advantage of him. He was always so poor all of his life, because everybody took advantage of him. 
                    <br /><br />

                    He became a follower of Buddha. When we were very active in the Mormon Church, we tried to talk him into coming to our church. Every now and then he would say that he would, and he would come, and then he would go back to the Buddhist religion. He did not believe in the Mormon Church until later. When he was 60 or 70 years old, he developed cirrhosis of the liver. It was because of his wild life in Hong Kong. He smoked, he gambled, he drank, he played with a lot of women, and so he developed hepatitis, and it developed into cirrhosis. The last two years of his life he was really weak. He started seeing the love of God in his life. He went on a cruise with us, a Mormon cruise, and learned about the Mormon Church. He started to believe, and then he was baptized. Then, a year later, he died. Before that, my mom was really against our church, and so he was not very active. He didn't get a chance to go to the temple. 
                    <br /><br />

                    After he died, my mom was still very against religion. I wondered, "How could anybody be so against religion?" I found out later on that my mom actually believed in God and Jesus Christ when she was growing up. Somehow someone preached to her when she was twelve and thirteen. But at that time it was World War II. Bombs were going off left and right. She went to wash dishes for restaurants at the age of twelve, and she would walk home in between bombs in Hong Kong. Her dad worked as a sailor for some European and American ships, and her dad would bring home some food for them. Otherwise they wouldn't have survived. That experience made my mom tough and strong, to the point that she didn't believe there was a God. She only believed there is war, there is money, there is power, and there are weaklings. If you are weak, you cannot survive. That was all she could remember. You have to depend on your own strength; there is no God. So the next 20 or 30 years of her life, she thought, “Why should you believe there is a God?” When I became a doctor, married, had kids, and then my husband died, that didn't help her, either. She still didn't believe there was a God. 
                    <br /><br />

                    The later decades of her life were not too bad. She was more stable then. Her husband was behaving better, compared to the wayward husband she used to have. When she was eight months pregnant with my brother, Gansin, she had to go up to the whore house to take my dad out of a bed with two other women. Living that kind of life, she was still hanging in there. It's amazing. My mom was a tough woman. For her to believe in deity was difficult. 
