            <span id="ChapterParagraphOne">
            <span id="BigFirstLetterText">I</span>t was hard for my mom to believe in God. The last two decades of her life, she seemed to have a pretty stable life. She had little health setbacks. She had a tumor in her belly which she got removed at Stanford. She had some precancerous cells in her cervix, and she had that removed. When she got older, two or three years before she died, she developed Parkinson's Disease, which had a little bit of an effect on her, but not very much. My work had slowed down a little bit, so I was able to spend more time talking to her. My children had graduated from high school and didn't need as much of my attention, so I started talking to her, watching videos with her, and explaining to her why God loved her. I still remember our conversation. I said, "Look, you had all of these tumors in your body, and even Stanford said it could be cancerous. Even your cervical problems were precancerous lesions. And God loves you! He cures your disease without you even knowing about it." After multiple explanations, she began to see the love of God. Subsequently she was baptized, approximately two years after my dad died.  <br />
