            <span id="ChapterParagraphTwo">
            
                She decided to follow Uncle Gregg to Hong Kong, and then in Hong Kong she had a stroke. She was half paralyzed and wanted to come back here, except the airline would not allow her to come back to America. I had to fly down to Hong Kong to pick her up and take her by ship to come back. When I first saw her in Hong Kong in the nursing home, I felt so bad. I said, “What's going on with my mom? She was so capable and functional, and suddenly she's in a wheelchair, not talking.” I felt sympathetic and full of compassion. And sad, too, because this was my mom, converting from one person to another person. I took care of her for three weeks on the ship and got to know her a little bit more, and after she came back to America she was living in my house and I spent more time explaining to her how lucky she was to have God to take care of her, to have her peace. I showed her a lot of videos, a lot of <a href="https://www.lds.org/general-conference/?lang=eng">General Conference</a>, and she began to understand more. A few months after she came back, she understood and wanted to go to the temple. I took her, and she really liked the temple. She believed there was a God now. 
 
            </span>

