            <div id="restofstory3" class="more">
                <span id="ChapterParagraphTwo">
                    She enjoyed the temple. She would be in her wheelchair using a tube to be fed—she could hardly even breathe—but she would dress herself so nicely on a Saturday, waiting for me to take her to the temple. I still remember one time I promised her that we were going to go with her, but last minute we couldn't go. She was so sad, so sad. I still feel bad! I still remember how she looked, and I feel bad. She was so happy going to the temple. 
                    <br /><br />

                    One thing I must say: for the longest time, I asked her for the ancestor file so that I could be baptized for our ancestors, and she would say, "No, no, no, no, no! I don't believe in your church." Then, after she came back from Hong Kong, she was half paralyzed. She could not stand, she could not walk, she could not eat, she could not breathe, she got a tracheotomy, she could not talk. But she could think very well. With all that, she was very sad. One day she said, "Evelyn, I don't want to live anymore, because life is so hard. You have to feed me with liquids. I cannot even eat solids. What is the point of living?" She wanted to die. At that point in time she wanted to leave the world because she was such an invalid, but each time she wanted to die, God wouldn't let her. She was just not dying, and she was not happy about it! But one day something changed in her, and she said, "I will give you the ancestor book." I got it, and within three months I had it converted into the computer file. I got the names and again I took her to the temple. I was supposed to be the first one who would start the ancestor file and do the endowment session. But for some reason I was called to attend to another duty, because I was also a worker there. So my mom turned out to be the first person who did the ancestor work for her entire line of 2,000 people. She was the first one who did it! After that I was the second one. A month later, she died peacefully. She went back to heaven peacefully. She got her wish to leave the world. Looking back at it, I think she was appointed to have this job all her life, and she was too stubborn to accept it. 
                    <br /><br />

                    My mom finally realized it was her calling to initiate baptism and endowment for her entire ancestor line, which had 2,000 people. It was amazing that all of these things came about. I couldn't do all 2,000 names; I was probably up to about 1,000 names. I got really tired, and I had some other responsibilities, and that was when I prayed to God. I said, "I cannot do these 2,000 names." At that very moment, someone contacted me, and said, "My ancestor is connected to your ancestor. I’ve done some names for you." I said, "Wow! Are you kidding me? You have done some names in connection with my ancestor names?" We met up where they were in Hawaii. They were descendants of one of our ancestors. I think it was God's response to me. Someone was there to help me finish the rest. They helped me finish half of it. I myself couldn't have done all of those names, because in those days, technology was not as good as it is now. It took half an hour in input one name, and so to input so many names was painstaking. But we did it and made it happen, and had all of the ancestor file, the names, and the endowments for all of that work. It was one of the indications that God exists. He answered my prayer out of the blue moon! I would never have imagined someone would call and say, "Your ancestor is connected to mine."
